  <section xml:id="sec-organizing-quantitative-data">
    <title>Organizing Quantitative Data</title>
    <definition>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  A <term>bar graph</term> is for qualitative data while
	  a <term>histogram</term> is used for quantitative
	  data. In a histogram, data is grouped into
	  <term>classes</term> or <term>bins</term>.
	</p>
	<p>
	  Notes on histograms:
	  <ol>
	    <li>Bars have equal widths</li>
	    <li>Bars are touching</li>
	  </ol>
	</p>
	<p>
	  Terminology related to histograms:
	  <ul>
	    <li><term>lower class limit</term>: smallest value in
	    a class</li>
	    <li><term>upper class limit</term>: largest value in
	    a class</li>
	    <li><term>class width (bin width)</term>: difference
	    between consecutive lower class limits (or upper
	    class limits)</li>
	    <li><term>open ended</term>: a table where the first
	    class has no lower limit and/or the last class has
	    no upper limit.</li>
	  </ul>
	</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <subsection xml:id="sub-distribution-shapes">
      <title>The Shape of a Distribution</title>

      <p>
	One reason for going through the trouble of displaying
	data in a histogram is to determine the basic shape of
